=========================================================
ABSTRACTION IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Abstraction is the process of exposing only the essential features of an
object and hiding the implementation details.

In simple words:

"What to do" is visible.
"How it is done" is hidden.

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED ABSTRACTION?
=========================================================

Without Abstraction:
• Users need to know implementation details.
• Increased complexity.
• Tight coupling.
• Difficult maintenance.

Abstraction provides:
• Simplicity
• Reduced Complexity
• Better Security
• Loose Coupling
• Easier Maintenance

=========================================================
REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
=========================================================

1. Car
------
You know:
• Start()
• Stop()
• Accelerate()

You don't know:
• Engine internals
• Fuel injection system
• Gearbox implementation

---------------------------------------------------------

2. ATM Machine
--------------
You know:
• Withdraw Money
• Deposit Money
• Check Balance

You don't know:
• Database operations
• Network communication
• Encryption mechanisms

This is Abstraction.

=========================================================
HOW IS ABSTRACTION ACHIEVED IN C++?
=========================================================

1. Abstract Classes
2. Pure Virtual Functions
3. Interfaces (using abstract classes)

=========================================================
EXAMPLE USING ABSTRACT CLASS
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Drawing Circle\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Shape* ptr = new Circle();

    ptr->draw();
}

Output:
Drawing Circle

User only knows:

draw()

User does not know:

How Circle implements draw().

This is Abstraction.

=========================================================
ANOTHER EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Database
{
public:
    virtual void connect() = 0;
};

class MySQL : public Database
{
public:
    void connect() override
    {
        cout << "Connecting to MySQL";
    }
};

Database* db = new MySQL();

db->connect();

Client only knows:

connect()

Implementation is hidden.

=========================================================
ABSTRACTION THROUGH INTERFACE
=========================================================

class ILogger
{
public:
    virtual void log() = 0;
    virtual ~ILogger() = default;
};

class FileLogger : public ILogger
{
public:
    void log() override
    {
        cout << "File Logging";
    }
};

Application depends on:

ILogger

Not on:

FileLogger implementation.

This is Abstraction.

=========================================================
ADVANTAGES OF ABSTRACTION
=========================================================

1. Reduces Complexity
