=========================================================
PARTIAL ABSTRACTION
=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    void display()
    {
        cout << "Shape";
    }

    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

display()
→ Implemented

draw()
→ Hidden implementation

This is Partial Abstraction.

=========================================================
COMPLETE ABSTRACTION
=========================================================

class IShape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
    virtual void erase() = 0;
    virtual ~IShape() = default;
};

All methods are pure virtual.

This is Complete Abstraction.

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is Abstraction?

Answer:
Abstraction is the process of exposing only essential information and
hiding implementation details.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Why do we need Abstraction?

Answer:
• Reduce complexity
• Hide implementation
• Loose coupling
• Better maintenance
• Better security

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. How is Abstraction achieved in C++?

Answer:
• Abstract Classes
• Pure Virtual Functions
• Interfaces

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Does C++ support complete abstraction?

Answer:
Yes.

Using interfaces (classes containing only pure virtual functions).

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Does C++ support partial abstraction?

Answer:
Yes.

Abstract classes can have both implemented methods and pure virtual
functions.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Is Abstraction same as Data Hiding?

Answer:
No.

Data Hiding:
Restricting access to data.

Abstraction:
Hiding implementation complexity.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Is Abstraction same as Encapsulation?

Answer:
No.

Encapsulation:
How data is protected.

Abstraction:
What functionality is exposed.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

Abstraction is one of the four pillars of OOP and refers to exposing
only essential behavior while hiding implementation details. It reduces
complexity and allows users to interact with an object through a simple
interface without knowing its internal working. In C++, abstraction is
achieved using abstract classes, pure virtual functions, and interfaces.

